second messenger cascades"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMetabotropic receptors function by \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivating G proteins to trigger second messenger cascades\u003C/strong\u003E. When a ligand binds to the receptor, it causes a conformational change that activates associated G proteins. These G proteins then interact with effector molecules to produce second messengers like cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) or inositol trisphosphate (IP3), which amplify the signal inside the cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForms direct ion channels across the membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes ionotropic receptors, not metabotropic receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphorylates target proteins directly\u003C/strong\u003E - Metabotropic receptors do not have intrinsic kinase activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransports molecules across the cell membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - Metabotropic receptors are not transporters\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds directly to nuclear DNA\u003C/strong\u003E - These are membrane receptors that do not interact directly with DNA\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key feature distinguishing metabotropic from ionotropic receptors is their indirect signalling mechanism through G proteins and second messengers rather than direct ion flow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metabotropic receptors activate G proteins which then trigger intracellular signalling cascades via second messengers.","G protein-coupled receptors have seven transmembrane domains and interact with heterotrimeric G proteins.","Unlike ionotropic receptors, metabotropic receptors do not contain ion channels within their structure."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18688"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62351"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:06:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11420"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationshi